      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/coefficient-and-standard-error-interpretation/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The voom method estimates the mean-variance relationship of the log-counts, generates a precision weight for each observation and enters these into the limma empirical Bayes analysis pipeline... The limma pipeline includes linear modeling to analyze complex experiments with multiple treatment factors, quantitative weights to account for variations in precision between different observations, and empirical Bayes statistical methods to borrow strength between genes.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly describes linear modeling with limma for differential expression analysis, coefficient estimation, and precision weighting.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2014-15-2-r29",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "coefficient-and-standard-error-interpretation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Extracting and validating linear model coefficient estimates and residual standard errors from microarray or RNA-seq differential expression analyses to quantify effect sizes and measurement precision.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:08:16.084739+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/coefficient-and-standard-error-interpretation/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Interest centers on testing whether one or more of the \u03b2gj are equal to zero... Differences in log-cpm between samples can be interpreted as log-fold-changes of expression.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper demonstrates that coefficient estimates (\u03b2) are used for hypothesis testing and fold-change interpretation.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2014-15-2-r29",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "coefficient-and-standard-error-interpretation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "These values form the foundation for downstream statistical testing and fold-change interpretation.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:08:16.084739+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/coefficient-and-standard-error-interpretation/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The above linear model is fitted, by ordinary least squares, to the log-cpm values ygi for each gene. This yields regression coefficient estimates \u03b2^g, fitted values \u03bc^gi=xiT\u03b2^g and residual standard deviations sg... We assume that: E(ygi)=\u03bcgi=xiT\u03b2g where xi is a vector of covariates and \u03b2g is a vector of unknown coefficients representing log2-fold-changes between experimental conditions. In matrix terms: E(yg)=X\u03b2g where yg is the vector of log-cpm values for gene g and X is the design matrix with the xi as rows.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes linear model fitting with design matrix X, coefficient estimation (\u03b2), and residual standard deviations (sg).",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2014-15-2-r29",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "coefficient-and-standard-error-interpretation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "After fitting a linear model to expression data using limma's lmFit function on a design matrix encoding experimental groups, inspect the resulting MArrayLM object to retrieve coefficient estimates (log-fold-changes) and standard errors.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:08:16.084739+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/coefficient-and-standard-error-interpretation/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We use linear models to describe how the treatment factors are assigned to the different RNA samples... Interest centers on testing whether one or more of the \u03b2gj are equal to zero.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper emphasizes that the design matrix must correctly encode treatment factors for valid coefficient interpretation.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2014-15-2-r29",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "coefficient-and-standard-error-interpretation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "If the design matrix is misspecified or does not correctly encode the experimental groups of interest\u2014coefficient estimates will be uninterpretable.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:08:16.084739+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/coefficient-and-standard-error-interpretation/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The log-cpm values are by definition normalized for sequencing depth. Other normalization steps can optionally be done... between-array normalization methods developed for single channel microarray data, such as quantile or cyclic LOESS, can be are applied to the log-cpm values.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper discusses normalization as essential preprocessing step affecting variance estimation.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2014-15-2-r29",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "coefficient-and-standard-error-interpretation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "If expression data have not been normalized and background-corrected\u2014standard errors will reflect technical noise rather than biological variability.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:08:16.084739+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/coefficient-and-standard-error-interpretation/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Borrowing information between genes is a crucial feature of the genome-wide statistical methods, as it allows for gene-specific variation while still providing reliable inference with small sample sizes... The normal-based empirical Bayes statistical procedures can adapt to different types of datasets and can provide exact type I error rate control even for experiments with a small number of replicate samples.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper emphasizes empirical Bayes borrowing strength between genes requires multiple replicates for stable variance estimation.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2014-15-2-r29",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "coefficient-and-standard-error-interpretation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "If interpreting coefficients from a single replicate per group\u2014empirical Bayes moderation cannot stabilize estimates without multiple replicates to estimate the prior.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:08:16.084739+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/coefficient-and-standard-error-interpretation/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "One popular differential expression pipeline is that provided by the limma software package [9]. The limma pipeline includes linear modeling to analyze complex experiments with multiple treatment factors, quantitative weights to account for variations in precision between different observations, and empirical Bayes statistical methods to borrow strength between genes.",
      "asbval:note": "limma is explicitly described as performing linear modeling and empirical Bayes moderation for coefficient and standard error estimation.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2014-15-2-r29",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "coefficient-and-standard-error-interpretation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "limma: Performs linear model fitting and empirical Bayes moderation to compute and stabilize coefficient estimates and standard errors across genes",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:08:16.084739+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/coefficient-and-standard-error-interpretation/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The results presented in this article were obtained using R version 3.0.0 and the software packages limma 3.16.2... The voom methodology proposed in the article is implemented in the voom function of the limma package. The limma package can be installed from the Bioconductor project repository.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms R as the host language for limma and describes using R for analysis workflows.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2014-15-2-r29",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "coefficient-and-standard-error-interpretation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "R: Host language for limma; used to load data, construct design matrix, execute lmFit and eBayes, and extract/inspect coefficient and standard error tables",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
