    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/empirical-bayes-variance-estimation/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The normal-based empirical Bayes statistical procedures can adapt to different types of datasets and can provide exact type I error rate control even for experiments with a small number of replicate samples. A key advantage of the limma pipelines is that they provide accurate type I error rate control even when the number of RNA-seq samples is small.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper explicitly states that empirical Bayes methods in limma provide robust inference with small sample sizes for both microarray and RNA-seq data, directly supporting the scope statement.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2014-15-2-r29",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "empirical-bayes-variance-estimation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Apply this skill when you have a fitted linear model (lmFit object) from microarray or RNA-seq count data and need to compute stable variance estimates and differential expression statistics despite having few biological replicates or small numbers of arrays.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:09:21.948691+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/empirical-bayes-variance-estimation/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The above linear model is fitted, by ordinary least squares, to the log-cpm values ygi for each gene. This yields regression coefficient estimates \u03b2^g, fitted values \u03bc^gi=xiT\u03b2^g and residual standard deviations sg... The voom methodology proposed in the article is implemented in the voom function of the limma package. The limma-trend method was implemented by inputting the log-cpm values from voom into limma's standard pipeline, with trend=TRUE for the eBayes function.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper describes the workflow as: (1) fit linear models to get residual standard deviations, (2) apply empirical Bayes (eBayes) to stabilize variance estimates. This is a post-hoc step after lmFit.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2014-15-2-r29",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "empirical-bayes-variance-estimation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Use it as a post-hoc step after linear model fitting to borrow information across genes and stabilize per-gene variance estimates before hypothesis testing.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:09:21.948691+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/empirical-bayes-variance-estimation/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The above linear model is fitted, by ordinary least squares, to the log-cpm values ygi for each gene. This yields regression coefficient estimates \u03b2^g, fitted values \u03bc^gi=xiT\u03b2^g and residual standard deviations sg. Also computed is the average log-cpm y\u00afg for each gene.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper confirms that linear model fitting (lmFit equivalent) must precede empirical Bayes variance estimation, supporting the 'When NOT to use' guidance.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2014-15-2-r29",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "empirical-bayes-variance-estimation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Input expression data has not yet been fitted to a linear model; use lmFit first.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:09:21.948691+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/empirical-bayes-variance-estimation/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Borrowing information between genes is a crucial feature of the genome-wide statistical methods, as it allows for gene-specific variation while still providing reliable inference with small sample sizes.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper emphasizes that empirical Bayes shrinkage is a key feature for borrowing strength across genes. If raw unadjusted estimates are needed, this method would not be appropriate.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2014-15-2-r29",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "empirical-bayes-variance-estimation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "You require raw, unadjusted per-gene variance estimates without prior regularization; empirical Bayes shrinkage is inappropriate for variance-only inference.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:09:21.948691+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/empirical-bayes-variance-estimation/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The normal-based empirical Bayes statistical procedures can adapt to different types of datasets and can provide exact type I error rate control even for experiments with a small number of replicate samples.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper emphasizes the advantage of empirical Bayes for small sample sizes but does not explicitly discuss when large sample sizes make shrinkage minimal or when standard t-statistics become preferable. The claim is reasonable but not directly supported by the paper's text.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2014-15-2-r29",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "empirical-bayes-variance-estimation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Sample size is very large (e.g., >100 arrays per group); shrinkage will be minimal and standard t-statistics may be preferable for computational efficiency.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:09:21.948691+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/gene-expression-linear-modeling/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "New normal linear modeling strategies are presented for analyzing read counts from RNA-seq experiments. The voom method estimates the mean-variance relationship of the log-counts, generates a precision weight for each observation and enters these into the limma empirical Bayes analysis pipeline... The normal-based empirical Bayes statistical procedures can adapt to different types of datasets and can provide exact type I error rate control even for experiments with a small number of replicate samples.",
      "asbval:note": "Core research question is directly supported by abstract and introduction. Paper demonstrates linear modeling with empirical Bayes for differential expression with small sample sizes.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2014-15-2-r29",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "gene-expression-linear-modeling",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Fit linear models to gene expression data (microarray, RNA-seq, or qPCR) to identify and quantify differential expression across experimental conditions. This skill applies least-squares regression with empirical Bayes moderation to stabilize variance estimates, enabling robust s",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:09:38.147519+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/gene-expression-linear-modeling/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "One popular differential expression pipeline is that provided by the limma software package [9]. The limma pipeline includes linear modeling to analyze complex experiments with multiple treatment factors, quantitative weights to account for variations in precision between different observations, and empirical Bayes statistical methods to borrow strength between genes.",
      "asbval:note": "limma is explicitly named and described as providing linear modeling and empirical Bayes methods. Functions lmFit and topTable are mentioned in Materials and Methods section.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2014-15-2-r29",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "gene-expression-linear-modeling",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "limma: Core package for linear model fitting, empirical Bayes moderation (eBayes), and differential expression testing via lmFit and topTable",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:09:38.147519+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/gene-expression-linear-modeling/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The voom method estimates the mean-variance relationship of the log-counts, generates a precision weight for each observation and enters these into the limma empirical Bayes analysis pipeline... Our strategy is to estimate non-parametrically the mean-variance trend of the logged read counts and to use this mean-variance relationship to predict the variance of each log-cpm value. The predicted variance is then encapsulated as an inverse weight for the log-cpm value.",
      "asbval:note": "voom is explicitly described as estimating mean-variance relationships and generating precision weights for use in limma pipeline.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2014-15-2-r29",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "gene-expression-linear-modeling",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "voom: Variance-stabilization transformation for RNA-seq read counts; computes precision weights accounting for mean-variance relationship prior to lmFit",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:09:38.147519+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/gene-expression-linear-modeling/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Library sizes were scale-normalized by the TMM method [54] using edgeR software [12] prior to the voom analysis... The different count-based packages implement different methods of compositional normalization [54].",
      "asbval:note": "edgeR is used for TMM normalization prior to voom analysis in multiple case studies. calcNormFactors is the standard edgeR function for this purpose, though not explicitly named in these passages.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2014-15-2-r29",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "gene-expression-linear-modeling",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "edgeR: Companion package providing calcNormFactors for normalization (TMM, RLE, etc.) and DGEList object creation; normalization factors are passed to voom",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:09:38.147519+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/gene-expression-linear-modeling/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The results presented in this article were obtained using R version 3.0.0 and the software packages limma 3.16.2, edgeR 3.2.3, baySeq 1.14.1, DESeq 1.12.0, DSS 1.4.0, PoissonSeq 1.1.2 and tweeDEseqCountData 1.0.8.",
      "asbval:note": "R is explicitly named as the programming environment used for all analyses.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2014-15-2-r29",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "gene-expression-linear-modeling",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "R: Programming environment for model fitting and statistical computation",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:09:38.147519+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/gene-expression-linear-modeling/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We assume that: E(ygi)=\u03bcgi=xiT\u03b2g where xi is a vector of covariates and \u03b2g is a vector of unknown coefficients representing log2-fold-changes between experimental conditions... The limma pipeline includes linear modeling to analyze complex experiments with multiple treatment factors, quantitative weights to account for variations in precision between different observations, and empirical Bayes statistical methods to borrow strength between genes.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly describes use of design matrices with covariates and treatment factors for linear modeling.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2014-15-2-r29",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "gene-expression-linear-modeling",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When to use: You have normalized or voom-transformed gene expression counts/intensities indexed by gene and sample, along with an experimental design matrix specifying condition, batch, or covariate assignments.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:09:38.147519+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/gene-expression-linear-modeling/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "An obstacle to applying normal-based statistical methods to read counts is that the counts have markedly unequal variabilities, even after log-transformation... We explore the idea that it is more important to model the mean-variance relationship correctly than it is to specify the exact probabilistic distribution of the counts.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper emphasizes the necessity of variance stabilization and mean-variance modeling before linear model fitting.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2014-15-2-r29",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "gene-expression-linear-modeling",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When NOT to use: Expression data are not yet normalized or variance-stabilized (apply normalization or voom transformation first).",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:09:38.147519+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/gene-expression-linear-modeling/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "A key advantage of the limma pipelines is that they provide accurate type I error rate control even when the number of RNA-seq samples is small... Typically G is large, in the tens of thousands or more, whereas n can be as low as three.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper indicates empirical Bayes works well with small n (down to 3), but the card's caveat about 'extremely small' and 'no biological replication' is a reasonable conservative interpretation of limitations.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2014-15-2-r29",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "gene-expression-linear-modeling",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When NOT to use: Sample size is extremely small (n < 3 per group) and biological replication is absent; empirical Bayes cannot robustly estimate variance trends.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:09:38.147519+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/gene-expression-linear-modeling/008",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "Paper does not discuss single-cell RNA-seq or zero-inflation issues. This is a reasonable extension of the method's scope but not explicitly addressed in the paper.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2014-15-2-r29",
      "asbval:supported_raw": null,
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "gene-expression-linear-modeling",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When NOT to use: You are analyzing single-cell RNA-seq where cell-level sparsity and zero-inflation dominate; consider zero-inflated or mixed-effects alternatives.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000302"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:09:38.147519+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000341"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/gene-expression-statistical-testing/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The voom method estimates the mean-variance relationship of the log-counts, generates a precision weight for each observation and enters these into the limma empirical Bayes analysis pipeline... The limma pipeline includes linear modeling to analyze complex experiments with multiple treatment factors, quantitative weights to account for variations in precision between different observations, and empirical Bayes statistical methods to borrow strength between genes. Borrowing information between genes is a crucial feature of the genome-wide statistical methods, as it allows for gene-specific variation while still providing reliable inference with small sample sizes. The normal-based empirical Bayes statistical procedures can adapt to different types of datasets and can provide exact type I error rate control even for experiments with a small number of replicate samples.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper explicitly describes empirical Bayes moderation for variance estimation and borrowing strength between genes for small sample sizes. B-statistics (log-odds) are mentioned in Table 1 output.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2014-15-2-r29",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "gene-expression-statistical-testing",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Apply empirical Bayesian moderation to gene-wise variance estimates in order to compute stable moderated t-statistics and B-statistics (log-odds of differential expression) from linear model fits of microarray or RNA-seq count data. This approach yields robust significance assess",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:09:54.864550+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/gene-expression-statistical-testing/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "One popular differential expression pipeline is that provided by the limma software package [9]. The limma pipeline includes linear modeling to analyze complex experiments with multiple treatment factors, quantitative weights to account for variations in precision between different observations, and empirical Bayes statistical methods to borrow strength between genes... The voom methodology proposed in the article is implemented in the voom function of the limma package.",
      "asbval:note": "limma is confirmed as the R package implementing empirical Bayes methods and linear modeling for gene expression analysis.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2014-15-2-r29",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "gene-expression-statistical-testing",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "limma: R package implementing empirical Bayes hyperparameter estimation (eBayes) and moderated t-statistic computation for linear models of gene expression",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:09:54.864550+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
