    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/gene-expression-statistical-testing/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "New normal linear modeling strategies are presented for analyzing read counts from RNA-seq experiments... This opens access for RNA-seq analysts to a large body of methodology developed for microarrays... The limma pipeline includes linear modeling to analyze complex experiments with multiple treatment factors...",
      "asbval:note": "The paper explicitly addresses linear modeling for differential expression testing in both microarray and RNA-seq contexts.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2014-15-2-r29",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "gene-expression-statistical-testing",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "You have fit a linear model to normalized gene expression data (microarray intensities or RNA-seq counts) and need to test for differential expression across experimental conditions or contrasts.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:09:54.864550+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/gene-expression-statistical-testing/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Borrowing information between genes is a crucial feature of the genome-wide statistical methods, as it allows for gene-specific variation while still providing reliable inference with small sample sizes. The normal-based empirical Bayes statistical procedures can adapt to different types of datasets and can provide exact type I error rate control even for experiments with a small number of replicate samples [3].",
      "asbval:note": "The paper emphasizes empirical Bayes borrowing strength for small sample sizes and type I error control.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2014-15-2-r29",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "gene-expression-statistical-testing",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Use this skill when sample size per group is limited (< 10) and you want variance estimates that borrow strength across genes to avoid inflated false positives from genes with spuriously low observed variance.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:09:54.864550+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/linear-model-fitting-for-gene-expression/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The above linear model is fitted, by ordinary least squares, to the log-cpm values ygi for each gene. This yields regression coefficient estimates \u03b2^g, fitted values \u03bc^gi=xiT\u03b2^g and residual standard deviations sg.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper demonstrates linear model fitting to gene expression (RNA-seq log-cpm) with design matrix X and coefficient estimates, but scope is limited to RNA-seq and microarray data. No mention of qPCR or proteomics applications in the passages.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2014-15-2-r29",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "linear-model-fitting-for-gene-expression",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Fit linear models to gene expression matrices using a design matrix encoding experimental groups or conditions, obtaining coefficient estimates and residual standard errors for downstream differential expression analysis. This skill applies to microarray, RNA-seq, qPCR, and prote",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:10:06.791731+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/linear-model-fitting-for-gene-expression/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "One popular differential expression pipeline is that provided by the limma software package [9]. The limma pipeline includes linear modeling to analyze complex experiments with multiple treatment factors, quantitative weights to account for variations in precision between different observations, and empirical Bayes statistical methods to borrow strength between genes.",
      "asbval:note": "limma is explicitly identified as providing linear modeling for gene expression analysis.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2014-15-2-r29",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "linear-model-fitting-for-gene-expression",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "limma",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:10:06.791731+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/linear-model-fitting-for-gene-expression/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The voom methodology proposed in the article is implemented in the voom function of the limma package. The limma-trend method was implemented by inputting the log-cpm values from voom into limma's standard pipeline, with trend=TRUE for the eBayes function.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms limma provides linear modeling functions and eBayes, but does not explicitly name 'lmFit' function in the passages provided. The function is referenced implicitly through the linear model fitting procedure described.",
